## Z-score Method for Outliers Detection and Removal

#### It's worth noting that a slightly relaxed threshold of 4.0 was used to avoid removing big portions of the data for interpretability purposes, while putting in mind to focus on tree-based models later in the modelling phase, which are robust in dealing with the remaining portion of the outliers



%%time
# Applying Z-score transformation to detect and remove outliers:

# A function that detects outliers using the Z-score,
    #then, returns the dataFrame with outliers removed.
def remove_outliers_z(transformed_data, columns, threshold=4):    
    
    df_cleaned = transformed_data.copy()
    outlier_summary = {}

    for col in columns:
        if col in df_cleaned.columns:
            col_zscore = zscore(df_cleaned[col].dropna())
            outliers = np.abs(col_zscore) > threshold
            outlier_index = df_cleaned[col].dropna().index[outliers]
            outlier_summary[col] = len(outlier_index)
            df_cleaned = df_cleaned.drop(index=outlier_index)
        else:
            print(f"Column '{col}' not found in the DataFrame.")
    return df_cleaned, outlier_summary


